    task_3_risk_weightings {
      domains [
        {
          domain Code and Repository Health,
          rating HIGH,
          rationale The Vault CRM re-platforming means the codebase is in active large-scale transition — legacy Salesforce-platform code, transitional adapter layers, and new native Vault code likely coexist, creating architectural debt accumulation risk precisely when it is hardest to manage. The multi-product Vault platform spans clinical, regulatory, quality, and commercial workflows — a sprawling codebase surface area with multiple domain teams that may have diverged in standards. Critically, in a GxP-regulated context, code change control is a regulatory compliance obligation, not merely a quality concern. Customer validation protocols are tied to specific software versions; uncontrolled changes or poor branch hygiene can invalidate customer GxP system validations, creating direct commercial and regulatory liability. The degree of legacy Salesforce dependency remaining in production is a specific question that must be answered with precision.
        },
        {
          domain Security Posture,
          rating HIGH,
          rationale Three mutually reinforcing factors drive this to high. First, data classification Vault hosts clinical trial data, regulatory submission dossiers, and quality management records among the most sensitive categories of enterprise data. A breach affecting clinical data could trigger FDAEMA regulatory inquiry beyond standard customer notification obligations. Second, regulatory mandates 21 CFR Part 11 and Annex 11 require specific, auditable access controls, electronic signature integrity, and audit trail immutability that are inspected by regulators — failures create product compliance deficiency, not just enterprise security risk. Third, the platform migration expands the attack surface, requiring security architecture review of new infrastructure boundaries, API endpoints, and authentication flows simultaneously with feature development. The Data Cloud segment adds data provenance, consent management, and re-identification risk. Assessment must cover FedRAMP-adjacent standards, SOC 2 Type II, ISO 27001, and GxP-specific controls.
        },
        {
          domain SDLC Maturity,
          rating HIGH,
          rationale SDLC maturity is the single most differentiating domain for life sciences SaaS. GxP-regulated customers require software suppliers to maintain formal validation packages — including requirements traceability, test coverage documentation, defect management records, and change control logs — as part of the customer's own regulatory compliance. Veeva is expected to operate a Computer Software Assurance (CSA) or equivalent framework. Weaknesses directly impair customers' ability to maintain regulatory compliance, creating commercial risk that can trigger contract penalties or customer escalation to regulators. The simultaneous execution of the Vault CRM migration, clinical EDC buildout, and AI feature development demands exceptional release management and regression testing discipline. SDLC immaturity in this context manifests as customer-facing defects in regulated workflows with consequences orders of magnitude greater than in non-regulated SaaS.
        },
        {
          domain Organization and Developer Health,
          rating MEDIUM,
          rationale Rates medium rather than high because Veeva's public track record, operating margin discipline, and tenure indicators suggest a reasonably well-managed engineering organization. However, several factors warrant scrutiny. The Vault CRM migration requires re-skilling engineers who built Salesforce-platform extensions — domain knowledge may not transfer cleanly to native Vault development. Key-person concentration risk in GxP-domain architecture is real engineers who understand the intersection of multi-tenant SaaS architecture and 21 CFR Part 11 compliance are scarce. India development centers warrant assessment for delivery quality integration and whether critical GxP-compliance-adjacent code has appropriate senior oversight. Engineering attrition would be a leading indicator of product quality degradation that takes 12-18 months to manifest in customer metrics — making current developer sentiment and retention data important forward-looking signals.
        },
        {
          domain Infrastructure and Cost Efficiency,
          rating MEDIUM,
          rationale Rates medium because Veeva's ~40%+ non-GAAP operating margins indicate infrastructure cost discipline is already strong. However, specific risks elevate this above low. GxP compliance imposes infrastructure architecture constraints not faced by horizontal SaaS audit trail immutability, data residency requirements for EU customers, validated backup and recovery procedures, and disaster recovery RPORTO commitments that must be formally documented and tested. Standard cloud infrastructure assessment frameworks will miss these dimensions. The Vault CRM migration involves infrastructure re-provisioning at scale creating a window of elevated risk. The Data Cloud segment involves high-volume data ingestion pipelines with different infrastructure profiles — cost efficiency and architectural separation of these workloads from GxP-regulated platform workloads deserves scrutiny. The question is not whether Veeva can afford its infrastructure but whether architecture is well-governed, regulation-compliant, and not carrying hidden technical debt in cloud configuration.
        }
      ]
